ss:/news/?p=40650", "http://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-057/library-of-congress-appoints-new-chief-of-serial-and-government-publications-division/", "http://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-057/", "http://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-057/library-of-congress-appoints-new-chief-of-serial-and-government-publications-division/2020-09-02/"], "campaigns": [], "date": "2020-09-02", "dates": ["2020-09-02T00:00:00Z"], "description": ["<p>The Library of Congress has appointed Deborah Thomas as chief of the Serial and Government Publications Division. Thomas brings more than 20 years\u2019 expertise working with digital collections and coordinating several of the Library\u2019s signature programs. She has served as acting chief of the division since December 2019.</p><p>Since joining the Library in 1998, Thomas has held numerous positions as an expert in the digital serials process. Her specialized knowledge of newspapers, metadata, born digital, collections accessibility and e-acquisitions has played a significant role in furthering the Library\u2019s institutional goal of developing a comprehensive management system in response to the transition from a traditional print to a digital media environment.</p><p>Thomas has served in a diverse set of roles since the start of her time at the Library.</p><p>Prior to her"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2020-12-12T14:15:48.093Z", "group": ["news", "wordpress-news"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-057/", "image_url": ["https://www.loc.gov/static/managed-content/uploads/sites/6/2020/09/Sized-deb-thomas.png#h=500&w=486"], "index": 28, "item": {"article": "<p>The Library of Congress has appointed Deborah Thomas as chief of the Serial and Government Publications Division. Thomas brings more than 20 years\u2019 expertise working with digital collections and coordinating several of the Library\u2019s signature programs. She has served as acting chief of the division since December 2019.</p><p>Since joining the Library in 1998, Thomas has held numerous positions as an expert in the digital serials process. Her specialized knowledge of newspapers, metadata, born digital, collections accessibility and e-acquisitions has played a significant role in furthering the Library\u2019s institutional goal of developing a comprehensive management system in response to the transition from a traditional print to a digital media environment.</p><p>Thomas has served in a diverse set of roles since the start of her time at the Library.</p><p>Prior to her role as acting chief, Thomas served as the Library\u2019s lead liaison for the National Endowment of the Humanities <a href=\"https://www.loc.gov/ndnp/\">National Digital Newspaper Program (NDNP)</a>. Thomas oversaw the growth of the program to include 50 states and territories, visiting more than 30 states to conduct site visits with program participants. In this capacity she also led the division\u2019s digital conversion team, which is responsible for the digitization of an average of 1.25 million pages of historical newspapers each year.</p><p>Thomas played a significant role in the Library\u2019s <a href=\"https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/\">Chronicling America</a> project, an undertaking by the Library and the National Endowment for Humanities to develop a searchable database of U.S. newspapers with descriptive information. Serving as the senior resource for the nationally-renowned program, Thomas provided deep expertise on the technical and programmatic management of the project, and ensured the database, which contains 17 million pages of newspapers, is readily accessible online.</p><p>\u201cDeb\u2019s success in helping establish the nationally renowned National Digital Newspaper Program and Chronicling America \u2014 one of the Library\u2019s signature digital programs \u2014 is experience that will help shape the division\u2019s approach to digital strategy, collections and access for years to come,\u201d said Eugene Flanagan, director of General and International Collections.</p><p>Thomas joined the Library in 1998 as a digital conversion specialist. In this capacity she led the coordination and implementation of the digital library project \u201cMeeting of Frontiers,\u201d an international bilingual Web archive of digital assets from Russian and Alaskan libraries and the Library of Congress.</p><p>Thomas has numerous publications based on her professional experience with the Library, including \u201cVoices and Viewpoints in Chronicling America: Uses of Historical News for Education and Outreach,\u201d and \u201cHelping Students Read Between the Lines: Identifying Bias and Attitude in the Press through Analysis of Newspaper Features Related to the Election of 1912.\u201d</p><p>\u201cI am excited for the opportunity to lead the division in both enhancing and extending the use of unparalleled print collections and to address the challenges of an increasing digital-only publishing world, meeting the needs and expectations of today\u2019s researchers,\u201d said Deborah Thomas.</p><p>Prior to her tenure with the Library, Thomas worked in web and database development. She began her career with the Smithsonian Institution\u2019s National Museum of American Art.</p><p>Thomas holds a bachelor\u2019s degree from the College of William and Mary and a certificate in publishing from Radcliffe College.</p><p>The <a href=\"https://www.loc.gov/rr/news/brochure.html\">Serial and Government Publications Division</a> was established in 1897 to administer acquisitions, bibliographic control, reference services and preservation activities for newspapers, periodicals and government publications. In the latter half of the 20th century, the Library was considered a pioneer in the use of micrographic technology to preserve newsprint serial publications on microfilm and is recognized today as an international leader in the digitization of newspapers.</p><p>The Library of Congress is the world\u2019s largest library, offering access to the creative record of the United States \u2014 and extensive materials from around the world \u2014 both on-site and online. It is the main research arm of the U.S. Congress and the home of the U.S. Copyright Office. Explore collections, reference services and other programs and plan a visit at\u00a0<a href=\"http://loc.gov/\">loc.gov</a>; access the official site for U.S. federal legislative information at\u00a0<a href=\"http://congress.gov/\">congress.gov</a>;\u00a0and register creative works of authorship at\u00a0<a href=\"http://copyright.gov/\">copyright.gov</a>.</p>", "contact_press": "Brett Zongker (202) 707-1639", "contact_website": "[https://www.loc.gov/rr/news/|Serial and Government Publications Division]", "division": ["serial_govt"], "image_caption": "Deborah Thomas is the new chief of the Serials and Government Publications Division at the Library of Congress. Photo credit: Abbie Grotke", "media_advisory": "0", "press_release_number": "20-057", "profile": "news", "short_title": "Library Appoints New Chief of Serial and Government Publications Division", "sub_headline": "Deborah Thomas to Oversee Collection of Historical Newspapers, Comic Books, Magazines and Government Publications", "topic": ["library_science"]}, "language": ["english"], "location": ["united states", "washington d.c."], "mime_type": ["text/html"], "online_format": ["web page"], "original_format": ["web page"], "other_title": [], "partof": ["news from the library of congress", "serial & government publications division"], "shelf_id": "20-057", "subject": ["personnel", "library_science"], "timestamp": "2020-12-12T16:22:42.913Z", "title": "Library of Congress Appoints New Chief of Serial and Government Publications Division", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-057/library-of-congress-appoints-new-chief-of-serial-and-government-publications-division/2020-09-02/"}, {"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["wordpress:/news/?p=40642", "http://www.loc.gov/item/prn-20-056/ame